Given eight courses with no prerequisites, there will be 80 operations, 10 per course. 
Given eight courses with eight prerequisites spread amongst them, there will be 112 operations, on average 14 per course,
1 cost per line. This puts the growth rate at 10 * N + (4 * P), simplified to O(N+P).

There isn’t a significant runtime difference between any of the available structures, other than the worse case for the binary tree structure. 
The binary tree structure has a faster search and access runtime than the linked list structure, and the hash table is faster than the binary tree structure,
according to the Big O cheat sheet provided in an earlier module. (Know thy complexities!). 
Given the requirements of the project and the code complexity of each structure, with the binary tree being the most complex and the linked list the least, 
the client might consider using a hash table for their project. 
